ce:section.ce:para:
Prior to the application of nanothermometer for sensing intracellular temperature, the cytotoxic effects of R-CDs on living cells were examined using a standard MTT assay. After R-CD exposure, Hela cells retained greater than 90% of their initial viability, even at 50 μg/mL of R-CDs (Fig. 7
                        ), proving that this nanothermometer has very low cytotoxicity. In addition, the bright red fluorescence of R-CDs was observed in the cell cytoplasm, and the morphology of the stained cells was retained (Fig. S14). Moreover, the fluorescence intensity of the stained cells exhibited no significant reduction after 30 min of R-CD exposure (Fig. S15), implying that this nanothermometer can be applied for living cell imaging. Furthermore, the temperature-dependent fluorescence intensity of R-CDs in living cells was investigated. As shown in Fig. 8
                        , the bright red fluorescence intensity became stronger when the temperature was elevated to 40 °C, indicating that R-CDs is capable of monitoring temperature fluctuations in living cells. Additionally, the average fluorescence intensities exhibiting temperature dependence were determined by use of commercial software (Fig. S16). The results showed that the fluorescence intensity values of the stained cells exhibited a temperature-dependent increase when the extracellular temperature was increased from 30 °C to 40 °C in living cells, indicating that R-CDs may serve as an excellent in vitro nanothermometer.
